1
00:00:23,107 --> 00:00:36,202
Stroke! Stroke!

2
00:00:55,472 --> 00:00:56,723
Come on, come on.

3
00:01:01,145 --> 00:01:03,312
Pick him up, pick him up.

4
00:01:03,397 --> 00:01:05,022
Son of a bitch!

5
00:01:05,107 --> 00:01:07,483
I mean, Your Honor,
that was a hell of a shot.

6
00:01:09,403 --> 00:01:12,280
Well, I'm currently doing an externship
for two extra credits

7
00:01:12,364 --> 00:01:14,449
as a clerk for Judge Hookstratten.

8
00:01:14,533 --> 00:01:16,868
B. J. Hookstratten?

9
00:01:16,952 --> 00:01:20,580
That's more impressive
than being in the top 5%.

10
00:01:20,664 --> 00:01:23,291
Look, I don't know what kind of offers
you've had from Wall Street...

11
00:01:23,375 --> 00:01:26,294
The top five, sir. In my class.

12
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:28,004
Not the top 5%. I'm sorry, I just...

13
00:01:28,088 --> 00:01:31,299
Mr. McDeere, we've just offered you
$68,000 a year

14
00:01:31,383 --> 00:01:33,760
from arguably
the leading law firm in Chicago.

15
00:01:33,844 --> 00:01:35,636
Is there somewhere else
you have to be?

16
00:01:35,721 --> 00:01:37,472
Yes, sir. I have a job.
I'm just on lunch break.

17
00:01:38,557 --> 00:01:40,349
I know you've had a lot of offers.

18
00:01:40,434 --> 00:01:43,394
Did you know, for example,
that we have 127 clients

19
00:01:43,479 --> 00:01:46,355
that are Fortune 500 companies?
Now, look, we'll offer you $74,000...

20
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:49,275
...our billing requirement for a
first-year associate is only 2,000 hours,

21
00:01:49,359 --> 00:01:52,528
not the usual 25 or 26 or 2,700.

22
00:01:52,613 --> 00:01:55,448
We want you
to have a life outside the office, Mitch.

23
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:58,284
And if you're a Lakers fan,
we have a fabulous box at the Forum.

24
00:02:04,792 --> 00:02:06,876
I know there are firms
from all over the country

25
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:09,420
that have been up here
offering you everything.

26
00:02:09,505 --> 00:02:12,632
But with your ability and ambition,
there is only one place for you,

27
00:02:12,716 --> 00:02:13,841
and that's with our firm in Washington...

28
00:02:13,926 --> 00:02:15,384
Let's stop talking about
the ribbon on the package,

29
00:02:15,469 --> 00:02:17,512
and start talking about
what's in the package.

30
00:02:17,596 --> 00:02:20,056
One of our partners is an ex-governor,
two are congressmen

31
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:22,141
and one's a former
Senator of Agriculture.

32
00:02:23,727 --> 00:02:25,853
May I take your coat, sir?

33
00:02:40,577 --> 00:02:41,744
- Mitchell McDeere, right?
- Yes.

34
00:02:41,829 --> 00:02:43,913
Lamar Quinn. Come on in.

35
00:02:44,832 --> 00:02:46,374
I'd like you to meet

36
00:02:46,458 --> 00:02:49,836
- Oliver Lambert, our senior partner.
- Mitch. Mitch.

37
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:51,587
- How do you do, sir?
- This is Royce McKnight,

38
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:52,797
- our managing partner.
- How do you do, sir?

39
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:54,799
- Welcome.
- Care for a drink?

40
00:02:54,883 --> 00:02:57,510
- No, I'm fine.
- Take a seat, Mitch.

41
00:03:01,014 --> 00:03:02,473
Tired of interviews?

42
00:03:02,558 --> 00:03:05,268
No, sir.
I just don't quite know what to say.

43
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:07,186
Unusual for a lawyer.

44
00:03:07,271 --> 00:03:10,398
I can get tongue-tied
in any number of situations, sir,

45
00:03:10,482 --> 00:03:12,900
but it's usually with my wife.

46
00:03:12,985 --> 00:03:16,487
Would you mind describing one,
with your wife?

47
00:03:18,574 --> 00:03:21,075
The first time I saw her.

48
00:03:21,159 --> 00:03:22,952
Any time we argue.

49
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:27,623
Whenever she walks into a room,
as a matter of fact.

50
00:03:27,708 --> 00:03:30,960
Might we ask
about the rest of your family?

51
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:34,380
My father was killed in the coal mines

52
00:03:34,464 --> 00:03:37,174
and my mother remarried
and lives in Florida.

53
00:03:37,259 --> 00:03:39,218
Brothers and sisters?

54
00:03:40,345 --> 00:03:41,554
None.

55
00:03:41,638 --> 00:03:45,433
Mitch, I hope
you don't think us intrusive,

56
00:03:45,517 --> 00:03:49,729
but stability in the family
has a special importance for us.

57
00:03:49,813 --> 00:03:53,608
Bendini, Lambert & Locke
is just a small Memphis firm,

58
00:03:53,692 --> 00:03:55,610
41 lawyers.

59
00:03:55,694 --> 00:03:59,822
But we're a large family.
So we're careful.

60
00:03:59,907 --> 00:04:03,326
Now, sir,
do you have any questions for us?

61
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:07,330
Do you have an offer in mind?

62
00:04:13,211 --> 00:04:16,255
It includes a bonus schedule,

63
00:04:16,340 --> 00:04:19,759
a low-interest mortgage
so you can buy a home,

64
00:04:19,843 --> 00:04:24,221
country club membership,
and we'll lease you a new Mercedes.

65
00:04:24,306 --> 00:04:25,348
You pick the color, Mitch.

66
00:04:25,432 --> 00:04:27,266
Lamar, you haven't been
paying attention.

67
00:04:27,351 --> 00:04:29,477
His wife picks the color.

68
00:04:35,067 --> 00:04:38,361
- Do I... Do I open it here?
- Of course.

69
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:41,155
Unless you can tell us what's in it.

70
00:04:42,950 --> 00:04:46,953
A lawyer worth that offer
shouldn't have to open the envelope.

71
00:04:54,962 --> 00:04:57,546
Mr. McKnight, you are
the managing partner

72
00:04:57,631 --> 00:04:59,674
at Bendini, Lambert & Locke,
is that correct?

73
00:04:59,758 --> 00:05:00,800
Yes.

74
00:05:00,884 --> 00:05:02,176
Did Mr. Lambert, as senior partner,

75
00:05:02,260 --> 00:05:05,054
give you any instructions
regarding my employment?

76
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:06,389
He did.

77
00:05:07,766 --> 00:05:11,435
And, Mr. McKnight, do you usually
follow Mr. Lambert's instructions?

78
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:14,647
Objection. Vague. Ambiguous.

79
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:16,107
Sustained.

80
00:05:19,069 --> 00:05:22,446
What precisely were those instructions?

81
00:05:22,531 --> 00:05:24,991
That you were in great demand,
and I should make certain

82
00:05:25,075 --> 00:05:29,453
that we obtained your services
before a bidding situation developed.

83
00:05:30,706 --> 00:05:33,332
How did you go about making certain?

84
00:05:34,501 --> 00:05:37,962
I bribed a clerk
in the Harvard Law placement office

85
00:05:38,046 --> 00:05:40,965
for the exact amount
of the highest offer,

86
00:05:42,259 --> 00:05:44,260
and then added 20%.

87
00:05:45,637 --> 00:05:48,931
Mitch, the letter you got
from Bendini, Lambert & Locke

88
00:05:49,016 --> 00:05:52,184
was the only one sent out. We want you.

89
00:06:20,839 --> 00:06:22,089
Okay.

90
00:06:22,966 --> 00:06:25,760
You're gonna have to leave now.
I'm expecting my husband.

91
00:06:25,844 --> 00:06:27,595
The hell with him.

92
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,139
Come here.

93
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:37,646
Moo shu pork, Szechwan beef,
mandarin duck from Wong Boys.

94
00:06:40,734 --> 00:06:42,109
It's even got a cork.

95
00:06:42,194 --> 00:06:43,861
What's going on?

96
00:06:44,488 --> 00:06:47,364
You remember the letter I got
from that firm in Memphis?

97
00:06:47,449 --> 00:06:48,824
Memphis?

98
00:06:48,909 --> 00:06:50,951
That's what I thought, until their offer.

99
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:52,578
What was the offer?

100
00:06:52,662 --> 00:06:55,581
They didn't say. It's in there.

101
00:07:01,171 --> 00:07:02,797
It's sealed.

102
00:07:02,881 --> 00:07:04,215
I guessed.

103
00:07:04,841 --> 00:07:06,050
What?

104
00:07:06,134 --> 00:07:08,427
Yeah, but I'm a good guesser.

105
00:07:17,270 --> 00:07:19,939
Plus a 5% increase the second year.

106
00:07:20,690 --> 00:07:22,358
Why?

107
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:25,820
"Why?" Whose side are you on anyway?

108
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:28,656
Yours.

109
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:31,492
Plus bonuses,
plus a low interest mortgage...

110
00:07:31,576 --> 00:07:33,202
As in a home, with grass around it?

111
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:36,914
They want to fly us down to Memphis
for a little visit.

112
00:08:04,067 --> 00:08:06,569
If you've been in one limo,
you've been in them all.

113
00:08:14,911 --> 00:08:17,371
Bye. See you later, Your Honor.

114
00:08:25,797 --> 00:08:27,089
Sir.

115
00:08:31,553 --> 00:08:33,053
Hey, Mitch.

116
00:08:33,763 --> 00:08:34,805
Come on, associates first,

117
00:08:34,890 --> 00:08:37,641
then lunch with the partners
in our private dining room.

118
00:08:38,852 --> 00:08:41,562
He's our number one draft pick,
so to speak,

119
00:08:41,646 --> 00:08:45,566
and he's being romanced
by the big boys

120
00:08:45,650 --> 00:08:47,776
from New York and Chicago
and everywhere else,

121
00:08:47,903 --> 00:08:52,114
so we have to sell him on
our little firm here in Memphis.

122
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:55,284
Meanwhile, he's gonna try
not to be embarrassed

123
00:08:55,368 --> 00:08:59,455
while I remind you that he's about to
graduate from Harvard with honors.

124
00:08:59,581 --> 00:09:00,623
Hear, hear.

125
00:09:06,922 --> 00:09:08,464
No one's divorced in the Firm?

126
00:09:08,590 --> 00:09:10,466
No one's divorced in the Firm.

127
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:13,135
- Impossible.
- No bachelors either.

128
00:09:13,803 --> 00:09:15,137
What about women?

129
00:09:15,222 --> 00:09:17,306
- They had one once.
- Only one?

130
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:20,559
Alice Krauss,
wobbled around on 4" heels.

131
00:09:20,644 --> 00:09:22,978
Affirmative action on stilts.

132
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:25,898
All white, all male, all married, huh?

133
00:09:32,739 --> 00:09:35,908
- What the hell is this?
- There he goes.

134
00:09:35,992 --> 00:09:37,159
Hey!

135
00:09:59,182 --> 00:10:01,016
It's different from the northeast.

136
00:10:01,101 --> 00:10:04,311
The pace, we're almost stately
by comparison.

137
00:10:05,021 --> 00:10:08,440
Courteous and not as gossipy.

138
00:10:08,525 --> 00:10:10,693
We keep each other's secrets.

139
00:10:10,777 --> 00:10:12,194
I like that.

140
00:10:13,488 --> 00:10:15,614
What do you like about it?

141
00:10:16,700 --> 00:10:20,119
All of it. It's a family.
Just the way you said.

142
00:10:29,045 --> 00:10:30,379
For the last three years,

143
00:10:30,505 --> 00:10:32,965
I've been teaching in the Boston area
at a private school.

144
00:10:33,049 --> 00:10:34,216
Do you work?

145
00:10:34,342 --> 00:10:36,802
Well, not since
I put Lamar through law school.

146
00:10:36,886 --> 00:10:38,804
But, you know, working isn't forbidden.

147
00:10:38,888 --> 00:10:41,390
- Forbidden?
- Working, by the Firm, you know.

148
00:10:41,474 --> 00:10:43,642
- How could it be forbidden?
- It isn't.

149
00:10:43,727 --> 00:10:47,813
Anyway, two babies in 14 months
and I had all the work I could handle.

150
00:10:47,897 --> 00:10:50,566
- Do you plan to start a family?
- Maybe in a couple of years.

151
00:10:50,692 --> 00:10:52,568
The Firm encourages children.

152
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:54,236
How do they do that exactly?

153
00:11:02,370 --> 00:11:04,580
Hey, how about it?

154
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:06,248
How about it.

155
00:11:09,002 --> 00:11:13,339
Okay, okay. The Love Boat band,
the secret recipe ribs,

156
00:11:13,423 --> 00:11:14,673
they're a little square maybe...

157
00:11:14,758 --> 00:11:18,093
I don't mind square. I like square.
Weird, I mind.

158
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:20,262
What do you mean, "weird"?

159
00:11:20,347 --> 00:11:21,597
Well, here's a quote.

160
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:25,684
"The Firm does not forbid me to take
a job, and they encourage children."

161
00:11:25,769 --> 00:11:27,353
Ask me why.

162
00:11:27,437 --> 00:11:29,021
Because they love kids.

163
00:11:29,105 --> 00:11:31,690
Because children promote stability.

164
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:34,193
Want to hear more?

165
00:11:36,112 --> 00:11:37,613
No, you're right.

166
00:11:38,239 --> 00:11:40,449
Don't pay any attention. I'm just gonna
throw myself over the rail.

167
00:11:40,575 --> 00:11:44,244
- I think my will is self-explanatory.
- Okay, okay, okay.

168
00:11:45,288 --> 00:11:46,955
These are nice people, Abby.

169
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:48,540
These are nice people. Okay.

170
00:11:48,625 --> 00:11:50,876
I'm more impressed with it than you are.
You grew up with it.

171
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:54,963
Do you know
what $96,000 a year is here?

172
00:11:55,090 --> 00:11:56,799
It's like 150 in New York.

173
00:11:56,883 --> 00:11:58,801
Did you ever think
I'd make a six-figure salary?

174
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:00,552
Absolutely.

175
00:12:01,471 --> 00:12:02,888
You did?

176
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:10,312
Well, your folks! Your folks
are only a few hours away, too.

177
00:12:10,438 --> 00:12:12,731
You mean, if we fight,
I don't have far to drive.

178
00:12:12,816 --> 00:12:14,316
Exactly.

179
00:12:22,617 --> 00:12:25,411
She made two phone calls
from the hotel,

180
00:12:25,495 --> 00:12:28,664
one to her parents
and one to the Memphis School Board.

181
00:12:29,999 --> 00:12:33,168
She seemed a little reluctant.

182
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:36,004
I'd hate to lose this young man.

183
00:12:36,089 --> 00:12:37,756
I think she'll come around.

184
00:12:37,841 --> 00:12:40,592
What about Kozinski and Hodges?

185
00:12:41,302 --> 00:12:43,637
Have you spoken to Chicago?

186
00:12:44,639 --> 00:12:46,014
I have.

187
00:12:48,017 --> 00:12:49,476
It's not good.

188
00:12:50,687 --> 00:12:52,312
We're gonna have to do something.

189
00:13:06,870 --> 00:13:09,163
I drew the happy face.

190
00:13:10,665 --> 00:13:12,499
Where's Memphis?

191
00:13:47,994 --> 00:13:49,161
Is that it?

192
00:13:49,245 --> 00:13:51,580
- Yeah?
- It looks different.

193
00:13:51,664 --> 00:13:54,583
It's prettier than the pictures they sent.

194
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:40,796
"Mitch and Abby, we've taken the liberty
of furnishing the house temporarily.

195
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,714
"Just a few things
to make you feel at home.

196
00:14:42,799 --> 00:14:44,466
"Hope you don't mind."

197
00:14:53,309 --> 00:14:54,601
Abby!

198
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:03,819
Not bad, huh?

199
00:15:04,821 --> 00:15:06,154
Where's yours?

200
00:15:23,172 --> 00:15:25,507
- Don't get up.
- Don't worry.

201
00:15:38,021 --> 00:15:39,605
Mitchell McDeere.

202
00:15:39,689 --> 00:15:41,315
Tad eager are we, Mr. McDeere?

203
00:16:30,031 --> 00:16:31,323
What are you doing?

204
00:16:31,407 --> 00:16:33,075
Dutch says you've been here since 6:30.

205
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:34,660
I thought
I'd jump start the bar exam work.

206
00:16:34,744 --> 00:16:37,079
Good. No associate
has ever failed the bar exam, you know.

207
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:38,914
Come on. I'll show you your new office.

208
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:40,832
Wally Hudson, Contracts.

209
00:16:40,917 --> 00:16:42,584
- Here to help with the bar exam.
- Thanks, Wally.

210
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:45,587
No associate of the Firm
has ever failed the bar exam.

211
00:16:45,713 --> 00:16:48,006
The first day
is a four-hour multiple choice on ethics.

212
00:16:48,091 --> 00:16:52,594
Look at the first six chapters.
I'll see you Wednesday, 8:45.

213
00:16:52,679 --> 00:16:57,182
Oh, no associate of this firm
has ever failed the bar exam.

214
00:16:57,266 --> 00:16:58,934
No kidding.

215
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:02,938
- Ken Curry. Domestic Relations.
- Mike Allen. Wills and Estates.

216
00:17:03,064 --> 00:17:04,606
Nina.

217
00:17:04,732 --> 00:17:06,358
Fuck! Please.

218
00:17:09,112 --> 00:17:10,737
I'm sorry. Can I help you?

219
00:17:10,822 --> 00:17:12,614
Actually, I think I'm here to help you.

220
00:17:12,699 --> 00:17:15,409
I'm Avery Tolar,
your designated mentor.

221
00:17:15,493 --> 00:17:16,660
Let's go to lunch.

222
00:17:16,786 --> 00:17:18,286
Lunch? But it's not even...

223
00:17:18,371 --> 00:17:21,540
Not even noon, I know.
It will be a working lunch.

224
00:17:21,624 --> 00:17:24,793
Come on up to my office
while I drop this off.

225
00:17:26,796 --> 00:17:28,004
Everything depends on billing.

226
00:17:28,131 --> 00:17:30,173
How many hours you spend
even thinking about a client.

227
00:17:30,299 --> 00:17:34,261
I don't care if you're stuck in traffic
or shaving or sitting on a park bench.

228
00:17:34,345 --> 00:17:35,804
Now, my particular field...

229
00:17:35,888 --> 00:17:38,140
Is forming limited partnerships
for offshore corporations,

230
00:17:38,224 --> 00:17:39,850
mainly in the Cayman Islands.

231
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:44,104
Good. I want you to review the last one
I did for a client named Sonny Capps.

232
00:17:44,188 --> 00:17:45,814
He made over 14 million last year,

233
00:17:45,898 --> 00:17:48,442
paid less than 4% in taxes
and resents every buck of it.

234
00:17:48,526 --> 00:17:52,279
But he paid us $400,000 in fees,
so I don't want to make him unhappy.

235
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:54,322
Take a look at the deal,
see if you can come up with anything.

236
00:17:54,407 --> 00:17:56,158
Madge, tell him
I'll call him in the morning, please.

237
00:17:56,242 --> 00:17:58,160
Yes, Mr. Tolar.
Should I save these for later?

238
00:17:58,244 --> 00:18:00,370
- Could you, please?
- What do you mean by "anything"?

239
00:18:00,496 --> 00:18:01,538
What do you think I mean?

240
00:18:01,664 --> 00:18:03,665
I don't know, you're the risk taker.

241
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:05,584
Do you think
I'm talking about breaking the law?

242
00:18:05,668 --> 00:18:08,253
No, I'm just trying to figure out
how far you want it bent.

243
00:18:08,337 --> 00:18:10,881
As far as you can without breaking it.

244
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:12,382
In other words, don't risk an IRS audit.

245
00:18:12,508 --> 00:18:15,218
I don't give a damn about an audit.
They just better not win.

246
00:18:16,345 --> 00:18:17,596
Yes, Mr. Tolar?

247
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:19,556
Something before lunch?

248
00:18:19,682 --> 00:18:23,727
I should warn you the Firm frowns
on drinking during office hours.

249
00:18:23,853 --> 00:18:25,353
